"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442510","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-13","<br /><p>All eligible students can apply for an upfront tuition fee loan to meet the costs of their tuition fees. This ensures that students are not prevented from attending their course because they cannot pay for their fees.</p><br /><p>From 1 August 2016 onwards, students who would otherwise have received a grant will see an increase in the amount of maintenance support they can access, with those from the most disadvantaged backgrounds receiving 10.3% more in loans for living costs.</p><br /><p>Linking repayment to a borrower's income will ensure that deductions are based on their ability to repay. Repayments are made through the UK tax system at 9% of earnings of any income over the relevant repayment threshold and they will cease if earnings fall below the threshold. Any outstanding loan balance will be written off after thirty years.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-01-13T17:30:39.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442510/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442510/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-05","Higher Education: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to reduce the cost of university for students.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","20939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442511","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-13","<br /><p>All regulations implementing EU legislation that were introduced in 2015 and their associated impacts can be found on legislation.gov.uk<em>. </em></p><p><em></em></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-13T17:36:03.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442511/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442511/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-05","Manufacturing Industries: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will estimate how many new EU regulations and directives have been implemented in the UK in 2015 which affect British manufacturing industries.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","21156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442512","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-11","<p>Unlike treaties, HMG does not maintain a central record of Memorandums of Understanding with third states. It is the responsibility of the lead policy department to file and record them.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-01-11T16:30:12.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442512/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442512/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442512/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-05","Government Departments: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which government departments have entered into a Memorandum of Understanding with another nation since 2010; and what the date was of each such agreement.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","20916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442513","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Government is fighting hard to fix the aspects of our EU membership that cause so much frustration in Britain - so we get a better deal for our country and secure our future. Departments are appropriately resourced to support the Government's priorities in Europe, including the renegotiation and referendum.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-13T17:03:57.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442513/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442513/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442513/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-05","Cabinet Office: European Union","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many staff in his Department are working on matters related to (a) European policy, (b) the future of Europe, (c) reform of the EU, (d) the renegotiation of the UK's relationship with the EU, (e) the EU referendum and (f) the consequences of the EU referendum; how many full-time equivalent staff are working on such matters; what the (i) staff and (ii) other cost of such work is; what proportion of that work is undertaken by such staff on (A) communications, (B) strategy and (C) policy; whether his Department has established any specific unit or units to deal with those matters; to whom such (1) staff and (2) units report; whether his Department has issued guidelines to staff on those matters; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","21072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442514","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-11","<p>Information about the diversity of the workforce in the Cabinet Office, including gender, is published on the Cabinet Office website and is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/cabinet-office/about/equality-and-diversity" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/cabinet-office/about/equality-and-diversity</a></p><p>under the heading Equality Information. As of 31 March 2015 there were 1,132 female (51%) and 1,109 male (49%) staff in post.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-11T13:53:19.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442514/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442514/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442514/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-05","Cabinet Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people of each gender work in his Department.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","21087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442515","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>Local Compliance Fraud merged with Specialist Investigation in 2015/16. Later that year Specialist Investigation then merged with Criminal Investigation to form one directorate, the Fraud Investigation Service (FIS). The figures for referrals to FIS are in the following table:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Taskforce Referrals Made</p></td><td><p>Adopted by FIS</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>336</p></td><td><p>52</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>598</p></td><td><p>145</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>596</p></td><td><p>276</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>The referrals are made by HMRC officers when they suspect or discover evasion. The process is designed to escalate this type of case to a specialist team for review. If the case is not adopted by one of these teams it is returned to the referring officer to continue the investigation.</p><br />","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-11T17:37:50.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442515/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442515/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442515/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many evasion referrals to the HM Revenue and Customs Evasion Referral Team were made by the taskforces established to crack down on tax evasion and tax avoidance in each tax year since 2012-13; and how many such referrals were adopted as working cases by the HM Revenue and Customs (a) Criminal Investigation, (b) Specialist Investigation and (c) Local Compliance Fraud business unit.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","21094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442516","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>The figures requested are in the following table:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Referrals made</p></td><td><p>Adopted CI</p></td><td><p>Adopted SI</p></td><td><p>Adopted LC Fraud</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2888</p></td><td><p>332</p></td><td><p>122</p></td><td><p>225</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>3298</p></td><td><p>387</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>217</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2749</p></td><td><p>374</p></td><td><p>146</p></td><td><p>129</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>The referrals are made by HMRC officers when they suspect or discover evasion. The process is designed to escalate this type of case to a specialist team for review. If the case is not adopted by one of these teams it is returned to the referring officer to continue the investigation.</p><p><br></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-11T17:36:43.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442516/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442516/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442516/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many evasion referrals were made to the HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) Evasion Referral Team in each year since 2012-13; and how many such referrals were adopted as working cases by HMRC's (a) Criminal Investigation, (b) Specialist Investigation and (c) Local Compliance Fraud business unit in each such year.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","21095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442517","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Treasury is in regular close contact with the FCA and the Prudential Regulatory Authority (PRA) on all issues relating to financial market conduct.</p><br /><p>Following benchmark cases on LIBOR, Foreign Exchange and Gold, the government passed legislation to regulate benchmark activities in UK. The administrators and submitters to <a href="http://www.fca.org.uk/firms/markets/benchmarks/our-powers" target="_blank">eight benchmarks</a>, including LIBOR, are now subject to the Financial Conduct Authority’s (FCA’s) standards of governance, controls, accountability, management of conflicts of interest and record keeping. This domestic regime will be superseded by the EU Benchmark Regulation when that enters into force.</p><br /><p>The European Parliament and the Council of the EU reached a compromise on an EU Benchmark Regulation on 24 November 2015. The Regulation brings in a set of rules to ensure that benchmark providers in the EU have prior authorisation and are subject to supervision, in line with internationally agreed principles drawn up by the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO).</p><br /><p>The government regularly engages with all the relevant European institutions to ensure that European-level regulations are strong and effective.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","21048","2016-01-13T15:43:47.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442517/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442517/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442517/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Financial Markets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with the European Securities and Markets Authority on the efficacy of current regulations to protect against the manipulation of the financial markets.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","21047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442518","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>HM Revenue and Customs do not hold the requested data.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-11T16:59:07.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442518/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442518/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442518/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many claimants of (a) working tax credit and (b) child tax credit have had their claims (i) stopped and (ii) suspended while HM Revenue and Customs processed a change in household circumstances in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","21092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442519","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Treasury is in regular close contact with the FCA and the Prudential Regulatory Authority (PRA) on all issues relating to financial market conduct.</p><br /><p>Following benchmark cases on LIBOR, Foreign Exchange and Gold, the government passed legislation to regulate benchmark activities in UK. The administrators and submitters to <a href="http://www.fca.org.uk/firms/markets/benchmarks/our-powers" target="_blank">eight benchmarks</a>, including LIBOR, are now subject to the Financial Conduct Authority’s (FCA’s) standards of governance, controls, accountability, management of conflicts of interest and record keeping. This domestic regime will be superseded by the EU Benchmark Regulation when that enters into force.</p><br /><p>The European Parliament and the Council of the EU reached a compromise on an EU Benchmark Regulation on 24 November 2015. The Regulation brings in a set of rules to ensure that benchmark providers in the EU have prior authorisation and are subject to supervision, in line with internationally agreed principles drawn up by the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO).</p><br /><p>The government regularly engages with all the relevant European institutions to ensure that European-level regulations are strong and effective.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","21047","2016-01-13T15:43:47.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442519/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442519/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442519/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","LIBOR","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with financial regulators to ensure that regulations on fixing the rates of the London Interbank Offered Rate are better enforced.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","21048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442520","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is an independent regulator. It is responsible for determining what information it publishes and when it is published, subject to statutory requirements. The Treasury will lay before Parliament any FCA reports or other documents which the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 requires to be laid before Parliament.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-11T15:50:30.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442520/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442520/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442520/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will place in the Library the unpublished 2015 reports produced by the Financial Conduct Authority in 2015 on banking culture.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","21130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442522","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>I have, following the recent Parliamentary debate on this issue, written to the European Commission and other Member States setting out our strong view that Member States should have full discretion over what rate of VAT they can apply to these products, and that this should be considered in the context of the Commission’s Action Plan on VAT initiatives. That Action Plan is now expected to emerge in March 2016.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-11T17:09:53.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442522/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442522/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking at EU level to make sanitary products exempt from VAT.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","21070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442523","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>The Government has no plans to introduce quarterly tax returns for business. The Government is introducing simple, secure and personalised digital tax accounts, removing the need for annual tax returns. Updating HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) through software or apps will deliver a light-touch process, much less burdensome and time-consuming than it is today.</p><p>The Government will consult on the details of these proposals throughout 2016 and will publish a Tax Information and Impact Note (TIIN) in the usual way. This will include an estimate of the impacts on business. The Government routinely publish TIINs for tax policy changes when the policy detail for those changes is finalised or near-finalised.</p><p>HMRC has discussed these reforms with a range of professional bodies and advisory groups representing small businesses and the self-employed. HMRC has also engaged extensively with a range of professional bodies and other stakeholders representing the accountancy profession.</p><p>On 14 December 2015, HMRC set out details of its plans at its annual stakeholder conference, which was attended by a large number of different organisations representing small businesses.</p><br />","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","20852 ; 20876","2016-01-11T16:54:15.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442523/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442523/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Taxation: Self-assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with organisations representing self-employed people on the potential effect on such people of implementing quarterly tax returns from 2020.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","21032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442524","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Government is fighting hard to fix the aspects of our EU membership that cause so much frustration in Britain - so we get a better deal for Britain and secure our future. Departments are appropriately resourced to support the Government's priorities in Europe, including the renegotiation and referendum.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-13T15:44:39.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442524/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442524/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Treasury: European Union","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff in his Department are working on matters related to (a) European policy, (b) the future of Europe, (c) reform of the EU, (d) the renegotiation of the UK's relationship with the EU, (e) the EU referendum and (f) the consequences of the EU referendum; how many full-time equivalent staff are working on such matters; what the (i) staff and (ii) other cost of such work is; what proportion of that work is undertaken by such staff on (A) communications, (B) strategy and (C) policy; whether his Department has established any specific unit or units to deal with those matters; to whom such (1) staff and (2) units report; whether his Department has issued guidelines to staff on those matters; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","21082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442525","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>It is the responsibility of each Department to ensure they have sufficient funding available to cover any additional costs associated with either the National Living Wage, the 3.4 per cent increase in Secondary National Insurance Contributions (NICs) from 2016-17, or the apprenticeship levy. HM Treasury has only made provision for the costs that it will incur in respect of its own staff as a result of these changes.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-01-11T16:22:00.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442525/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442525/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what provision his Department has made for public sector employers to pay the (a) national living wage, (b) 3.4 per cent increase in Secondary National Insurance Contributions (NICs) from 2016-17 following the abolition of Contracted Out NICs and (c) Apprenticeship Levy.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","21093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442526","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-13","<p>The information requested could only be provided at a disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-13T15:41:42.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442526/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442526/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Working Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many claimants of working tax credit (WTC) had an in-year change of circumstances to their income which required a change to their WTC entitlement in each year since 2009-10; how many such claimants' entitlements (a) reduced and (b) increased; and what the net change in receipts to the Exchequer was as a result of these adjustments in that period.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442527","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-13","<p>Spending Review 2015 prioritised housing by doubling the housing budget from 2018-19 to deliver at least 400,000 new affordable homes. It sets out the most ambitious plan since the 1970s to build homes that support working people in their aim to buy their own home.</p><p>Taken together the capital programme, loan schemes, Help to Buy and other measures amount to over £20 billion investment in housing over the Spending Review period.</p><p>The detailed list of housing programmes for 2016-17 to 2020-21 is outlined in the five point Housing plan in the Spending Review 2015 document (pp. 40-42).</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-13T17:24:30.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442527/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442527/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-05","Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the expected investment spending on housing by central government will be between 2016-17 and 2020-21.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","20973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442528","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-13","<p>Members of the Government’s Council of Economic Advisers meet every day to discuss the design and formation of government policy. Details of the Council’s membership and remuneration are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs-december-2015</a>. The Council operates from HM Treasury. Running costs cannot be disaggregated from the department’s budget.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","21112 ; 21113","2016-01-13T15:50:37.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442528/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442528/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Council of Economic Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the annual running cost is of the Council of Economic Advisers; and what office space that council is allocated within the government estate.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","20997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442529","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-13","<p>No payments were made to the Government Property Unit for rent during 2015-16 as rent for buildings is instead paid directly to the relevant landlord. We estimate no payments will become due to the Government Property Unit during the remainder of the period.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-13T15:45:42.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442529/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442529/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442529/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Treasury: Rents","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the amount that his Department will pay to the Government Property Unit in rent for buildings in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","20998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442530","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>HM Treasury has no knowledge of a recent report concluded by the FCA on retail investment advice. If the Honourable Member is referring to the recent Financial Advice Market Review, which was a joint initiative by HM Treasury and the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) launched in August 2015, this review has not yet concluded.</p><br /><p>The Treasury will lay before Parliament any FCA reports or other documents which the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000 requires to be laid before Parliament.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-11T15:51:49.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442530/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442530/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Financial Services: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will place in the Library the report recently concluded by the Financial Conduct Authority on retail investment advice.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","21007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442531","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>In January 2015, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) published its Cash Savings Market Study report, which found that competition in the cash savings market was not working well for many consumers. In response, the FCA has consulted on and will subsequently be introducing new rules from 1 December 2016 designed to improve competition by encouraging easier and quicker switching and improving the information savers receive.</p><br /><p>These new rules will require firms to provide key information in a product summary box at point of sale and to be clear on what interest rate consumers are getting. The FCA will also introduce a new rule which requires firms to provide a prompt and efficient service so that a customer can switch to a better account offered by the same firm.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-11T15:29:20.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442531/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442531/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Personal Savings: Interest Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will discuss with the Financial Conduct Authority the effect of the savings products offered by providers with almost zero interest rates on people with savings.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","20934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442532","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>The vast majority of Self Assessment customers complete their returns on time (92% last year).</p><br /><p>This year, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is sending millions of targeted emails and texts to remind customers to submit their return by 31 January, for instance to customers who missed the deadline last year or those who are new to Self Assessment. Alongside this, HMRC is running a national marketing campaign to remind customers of the 31 January deadline. Support is available to those who need it as HMRC is putting hundreds of extra people on its helplines during this very busy period, and has introduced new support channels like webchat and online video guidance.</p><br />","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-11T16:57:15.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442532/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442532/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Taxation: Self-assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps are being taken to ensure the maximum number of people meet the 31 January 2016 deadline for providing their tax returns.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","20935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442533","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-13","<p>Members of the Government’s Council of Economic Advisers meet every day to discuss the design and formation of government policy. Details of the Council’s membership and remuneration are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs-december-2015</a>. The Council operates from HM Treasury. Running costs cannot be disaggregated from the department’s budget.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","20997 ; 21113","2016-01-13T15:50:37.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442533/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442533/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Council of Economic Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, who the members of his Council of Economic Advisers are; and what remuneration each such member receives for that role.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","21112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442534","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-13","<p>Members of the Government’s Council of Economic Advisers meet every day to discuss the design and formation of government policy. Details of the Council’s membership and remuneration are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-adviser-data-releases-numbers-and-costs-december-2015</a>. The Council operates from HM Treasury. Running costs cannot be disaggregated from the department’s budget.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","20997 ; 21112","2016-01-13T15:50:37.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442534/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442534/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-05","Council of Economic Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the Council of Economic Advisers (a) last met and (b) will next meet.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","21113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442535","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>It is for local authorities to decide how to disburse their funds, and what if any conditions to attach to any grants or contributions they make available, in accordance with the functions Parliament has given them and their duties to secure value for money in the use of taxpayers’ money.</p><p>Local authorities are accountable to their electorate, including for their use of taxpayers’ money and any member of the public with a concern about the way in which a local authority is using public money should take the matter up with the local authority directly, or contact the local authority’s independent auditor.</p><p>We will keep these matters under review and are open to representations on this issue.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-01-14T16:58:04.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442535/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442535/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-05","Local Government: Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Written Statement of 23 February 2015, HCW5292, if he will extend the anti-sock puppet clause to cover the issuing of grants and contracts made by local authorities in respect to the activities of third parties.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","21153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442536","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Government expects to secure at least 500 sites for starter homes through the use of the new £1.2 billion starter home land fund. These sites will be identified over the next three years, working closely with local planning authorities and developers. Further details about the operation of the fund will be announced in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-13T11:35:24.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442536/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442536/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-05","First Time Buyers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the announcement of 4 January 2016, on which 500 new sites the Government plans to directly build affordable homes, at least 30,000 new starter homes and up to 30,000 market homes by 2020.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","20922"
