/p></td><td><p>84.1%</p></td><td><p>95%</p></td><td><p>86.8%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>It is not possible to provide the figure for applications from Hampstead and Kilburn constituency as this information is not collected.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-01-14T16:07:47.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442716/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442716/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-05","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of applications for Disclosure and Barring Service checks (a) nationally, (b) in London and (c) in Hampstead and Kilburn constituency met each of the service's published service standards for waiting times in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442717","Home Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Home Office holds reportable information on the number of failed asylum seekers who submit a further submission and how long their case remained outstanding. Permission to work requests are documented on the immigration casework database, but the information is not extractable without interrogating thousands of individual records. Therefore, the information is not readily available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-01-12T16:14:52.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442717/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442717/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-05","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for how many asylum applications initially rejected by UK Visas and Immigration did applicants subsequently make further submissions which were more than 12 months old; how many such applicants submitted a request to be allowed to work in the UK; how many of those requests to work were rejected; and how long, on average, did it take for those accepted to be given documents confirming their right to work in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442718","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-11","<p>Whilst the Ross Fund is not directly focused on HIV and AIDS, the UK continues to invest in research on HIV and AIDS. This includes research into understanding the structural drivers that can increase HIV (including gender inequality, stigma and limited livelihood opportunities), HIV prevention technologies (such as microbicides and vaccines) and studies to identify cost-effective ways to deliver HIV services.</p><p /> <p>The Ross Fund will target infectious diseases including malaria, diseases with epidemic potential, neglected tropical diseases which affect over a billion people globally, and antimicrobial resistance which poses a substantial and growing threat to global health. The goal of the Ross fund is to develop, test and deliver a range of new products (including vaccines, drugs and diagnostics) to help combat these diseases in developing countries.</p><br />","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-01-11T16:16:13.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442718/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442718/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-05","Developing Countries: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether the Ross Fund will include funding to tackle HIV/AIDS; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","20995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442719","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Government is fighting hard to fix the aspects of our EU membership that cause so much frustration in Britain - so we get a better deal for Britain and secure our future. Departments are appropriately resourced to support the Government's priorities in Europe, including the renegotiation and referendum.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-01-13T16:14:01.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442719/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442719/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-05","Department for International Development: European Union","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many staff in her Department are working on matters related to (a) European policy, (b) the future of Europe, (c) reform of the EU, (d) the renegotiation of the UK's relationship with the EU, (e) the EU referendum and (f) the consequences of the EU referendum; how many full-time equivalent staff are working on such matters; what the (i) staff and (ii) other cost of such work is; what proportion of that work is undertaken by such staff on (A) communications, (B) strategy and (C) policy; whether her Department has established any specific unit or units to deal with those matters; to whom such (1) staff and (2) units report; whether her Department has issued guidelines to staff on those matters; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","21080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442720","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-12","<p>The UK has been at the forefront of the response to the crisis in Syria and the region. We have pledged over £1.1 billion to date, our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis.</p><br /><p>UK support has reached hundreds of thousands of people in Syria, Jordan, Lebanon, Turkey, Iraq and Egypt. We are supporting refugees to remain in host countries in the region, and supporting host countries to accommodate them. The table below provides a breakdown of DFID funding spent through partners to respond to the impact of the Syria crisis in Jordan, Iraq and Israel since 2011/2012.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>DFID Funding for Humanitarian/Development Activities in Jordan, Iraq and Israel in response to the Syria refugee crisis (excluding funding to the Conflict Security and Stabilisation Fund) </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Jordan</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Iraq</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Israel </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/2012</strong></p></td><td><p>£0</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/2013</strong></p></td><td><p>£17,650,797</p></td><td><p>£2,302,769</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/2014</strong></p></td><td><p>£68,882,422</p></td><td><p>£11,223,595</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/2015</strong></p></td><td><p>£47,572,254</p></td><td><p>£5,563,464</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>DFID does not provide funding for projects in Israel, which is a high-income country, and therefore ineligible for Official Development Assistance.</p><br />","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-01-12T14:30:05.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442720/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442720/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-05","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2015 to Question 19712, how much funding her Department provided to (a) Jordan, (b) Iraq and (c) Israel to assist with the effect of the refugee crisis in Syria in each year since 2011-12.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442721","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-11","<p>The UN Population Division estimates that total average life expectancy for fifteen year old girls in Sub-Saharan Africa was 63.53 years between 2005 and 2010 and 66.12 years between 2010 and 2015.</p><br />","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-01-11T16:13:54.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442721/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442721/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-05","Sub-Saharan Africa: Life Expectancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what information her Department holds on the average life expectancy for girls aged 15 in sub-Saharan Africa between 2005 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","20932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442722","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-07","<p>Barbados does not qualify for Official Development Assistance (ODA) by the Department for International Development under internationally agreed ODA criteria.</p><br />","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-01-07T10:44:05.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442722/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442722/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-05","Barbados: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make it her policy to provide aid to Barbados; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","20920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442723","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-11","<p>No work has been undertaken by the Ministry of Justice as a result of the Memorandum of Understanding. No discussions are taking place between the Ministry of Justice and Saudi officials under the terms of the Memorandum.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-01-11T15:09:58.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442723/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442723/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-05","Prisons: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether discussions are still taking place between UK and Saudi officials under the terms of the Memorandum of Understanding signed in October 2014.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","20937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442724","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-11","<p>Policy responsibility for this area lies with the Home Office. The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) has powers to intercept prisoners’ communications in specific circumstances.</p><p>Section 4(4) of the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000 (RIPA) provides that the interception of communications in prisons is authorised where the conduct is in exercise of a power conferred by the Prison Rules. The Prison Rules allow for interception of a prisoner’s communications if it is necessary on certain specified grounds and proportionate to what is sought to be achieved<em>.</em> The Prison Rules do not permit interception of a prisoner’s communication with the prisoner’s legal adviser, unless the governor of the prison has reasonable cause to believe that the communication is being made with the intention of furthering a criminal purpose and unless authorised by the Chief Executive Officer of NOMS; the director responsible for the national operational services of NOMS; or the duty director of NOMS.</p><br />","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-11T11:20:00.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442724/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442724/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-05","Rights of Accused","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions he has had with the Home Secretary on proposed legislative steps to protect legally privileged communications from surveillance.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","20942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442725","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-13","<p>The information on the number of additional days awarded to prisoners in each prison establishment as a result of adjudications in each year since 2010 can be found in the attached table although figures for 2015 are not yet available.</p><p>Discipline procedures are central to the maintenance of a safe custodial environment. They are provided for by the Prison and Young Offender Institution Rules which require adjudications to be conducted lawfully, fairly and justly, and for prisoners and young people (aged 15-17) to have a full opportunity to hear what is alleged against them and to present their case. Independent Adjudicators are District Judges or Deputy District Judges who attend prisons and Young Offender Institutions when necessary to hear adjudication cases which are deemed sufficiently serious. These cases may merit a punishment of additional days to a prisoner’s time spent in custody if the prisoner or young person is found guilty. Only Independent Adjudicators can make an award of additional days as a punishment.</p><p>A range of safeguarding measures are in place to make sure that a prisoner or young person is physically and mentally fit to face an adjudication hearing and any subsequent punishment.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-13T15:02:46.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442725/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442725/answer","20908 - table.xlsx","20908 - table.xlsx","Number of Instances and Days from 2010-14","Number of Instances and Days from 2010-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442725/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-05","Prisons: Discipline","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many days were added in each prison establishment as a result of adjudications in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","20908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442726","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-11","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) does not collect information on the average time between the date of final submission of papers for an immigration appeal and the date of the hearing.</p><br /><p>The average time between the date of receipt of an appeal and the date of the hearing in the 12 months up to 30 September 2015 was 23 weeks.</p><br /><p>HMCTS has allocated additional court time between December 2015 and March 2016 to ensure current waiting times for hearings are maintained.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-01-11T16:12:33.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442726/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442726/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-05","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average time was between the date of final submission of papers for an immigration appeal and the date of the hearing in the last 12 months for which figures are available; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Damian Green","Ashford","Damian Green","20906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442727","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Government is fighting hard to fix the aspects of our EU membership that cause so much frustration in Britain - so we get a better deal for Britain and secure our future. Departments are appropriately resourced to support the Government's priorities in Europe, including the renegotiation and referendum.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-01-13T12:06:42.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442727/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442727/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-05","Ministry of Justice: European Union","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff in his Department are working on matters related to (a) European policy, (b) the future of Europe, (c) reform of the EU, (d) the renegotiation of the UK's relationship with the EU, (e) the EU referendum and (f) the consequences of the EU referendum; how many full-time equivalent staff are working on such matters; what the (i) staff and (ii) other cost of such work is; what proportion of that work is undertaken by such staff on (A) communications, (B) strategy and (C) policy; whether his Department has established any specific unit or units to deal with those matters; to whom such (1) staff and (2) units report; whether his Department has issued guidelines to staff on those matters; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","21081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442728","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>I have had no discussions with the Northern Ireland Executive on tackling isolation of women living in rural areas.</p><p>I have general discussions with Ministers in the Executive on a range of issues and this has included providing more opportunities for women to participate in political and public life. During the recent cross party talks, I also highlighted the importance of engaging women in community initiatives to combat the influence of paramilitary groupings. This is reflected in the Fresh Start Agreement.</p><p>The Government recognises the lack of female representation in politics and public life and further recognises the positive outcomes that result in tackling this inequality. As the 2015 Conservative Manifesto said: “We also want to increase the proportion of public appointments going to women in the next Parliament, as well as the number of female MPs.”</p><p>I have attended a number of events meeting women’s groups from across Northern Ireland and discussed the role of women in civic society and politics. This includes speaking at the Women’s Engagement Roadshow event in Belfast which highlighted the work Government is doing to improve the lives of women, and also provided women with a forum to voice their concerns about the issues that are important to them.</p><p>I welcome the fact that on 11 January Arlene Foster became Northern Ireland’s first woman First Minister.</p><br />","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-01-13T15:28:00.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442728/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442728/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-05","Females: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with the Northern Ireland Executive on (a) tackling isolation of women living in rural areas and (b) providing more opportunities for women to participate in political and public life.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","21031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442729","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Northern Ireland Office has a co-ordinating role as part of the Government’s overall efforts to commemorate the centenaries of World War One events. Our aim is to ensure that these events, including for the Battle of the Somme, are commemorated in Northern Ireland in a manner which promotes reconciliation and enhances prospects for a peaceful, shared future.</p><p>Officials from my Department sit on the Department for Culture, Media and Sport Programme Board for First World War Centenary Commemorations. They also have regular contact with officials in the Northern Ireland Executive and sit on the Northern Ireland First World War Centenary Committee chaired by Jeffrey Donaldson MP.</p><p>I receive regular updates on this work and both the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State and I will be in attendance at a number of events being planned to mark the Battle of the Somme centenary. These events will take place in Northern Ireland and France.</p><br />","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-01-12T12:49:29.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442729/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442729/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-05","World War I: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what plans the Government has to mark the centenary of the outbreak of the Battle of the Somme in Northern Ireland; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","21146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442730","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>The centenary commemorations of the First World War, including the Battle of the Somme, and the wider decade of 1912-1922 offer an important opportunity to reflect on the shared history between the United Kingdom and Ireland.</p><p>The Prime Minister is committed, along with the Taoiseach, to commemorating our past with mutual respect and understanding. The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State and I are working with Ministers in the Irish Government to mark the events of this decade. I have discussed these matters on a number of occasions with them.</p><p>Marking anniversaries such as the Battle of the Somme in a spirit of historical accuracy, mutual respect and inclusiveness can support efforts to build a peaceful and shared future for everyone in Northern Ireland.</p><p>Officials from my Department have regular contact with officials in the Irish Government regarding their programme of events to mark the anniversary of the Battle of the Somme, which was announced in November 2015, and I receive regular updates on this work.</p><br />","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-01-12T12:53:40.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442730/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442730/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-05","World War I: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether she has had discussions with Ministers in the Irish government on marking the centenary of the start of the Battle of the Somme this year; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","21147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442731","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-01-12","One of the Northern Ireland Office’s key objectives for the commemoration of the decade of centenaries of 1912-1922 is to work with the Irish Government to promote greater understanding of our shared history. I understand that the Irish Government launched its programme for the centenary of the Easter Rising on 12 November 2014. To date, the Northern Ireland Office has not received any invitations to attend the planned events in Dublin.","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-01-12T12:56:50.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442731/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442731/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-05","Easter Rising: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether the Northern Ireland Office has been invited by the Irish government to take any part in events planned to mark the centenary of the Easter Uprising in Dublin; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","21148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442732","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>I have participated in general discussions with colleagues, including the Home Secretary, on the resettlement of Syrian refugees in the UK. The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State sits on the Government’s Syrian Refugee Relocation Ministerial Group.</p><p>The Home Office are working with local authorities and the Devolved Administrations, including the Northern Ireland Executive, to put in place the necessary arrangements for the resettlement of Syrian refugees. My Department is in regular contact with the Home Office about these matters.</p><br />","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","21150","2016-01-13T15:30:04.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442732/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442732/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-05","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with the Secretary of State for Home Affairs on the resettlement in Belfast of those Syrian refugees who arrived in Northern Ireland before Christmas 2015; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","21149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442733","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>I have participated in general discussions with colleagues, including the Home Secretary, on the resettlement of Syrian refugees in the UK. The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State sits on the Government’s Syrian Refugee Relocation Ministerial Group.</p><p>The Home Office are working with local authorities and the Devolved Administrations, including the Northern Ireland Executive, to put in place the necessary arrangements for the resettlement of Syrian refugees. My Department is in regular contact with the Home Office about these matters.</p><br />","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","21149","2016-01-13T15:30:04.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442733/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442733/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-05","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with the Home Secretary on the next phases of the resettlement of Syrian refugees in Northern Ireland, including the numbers of refugees to be resettled in 2016; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","21150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442734","Home Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>The recent judgement of the Investigatory Powers Tribunal on the Wilson Doctrine details the safeguards in the Interception Code of Practice and the Security and Intelligence Agencies’ guidance for the protection of Parliamentarians’ communications.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-01-12T15:38:39.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442734/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442734/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-05","Members: Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Prime Minister's Written Statement of 4 November 2015 on the Wilson Doctrine, whether measures are in place to prevent the security services reading an hon. Member's correspondence by using unusual search terms likely to bring up parliamentary correspondence of particular hon. Members held as a result of the bulk collection of electronic data.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","21106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442735","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>The draft franchise agreements are already published by the Department:</p><p>TransPennine Express (TPE): <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/417830/franchise-agreement.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/417830/franchise-agreement.pdf</a></p><p>Northern: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/417807/northern-franchise-agreement.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/417807/northern-franchise-agreement.pdf</a></p><p>and the final agreements will be published after the agreed redactions have taken place.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-11T15:15:57.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442735/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442735/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Written Statement of 9 December 2015 HDVS 369 on rail franchising, when he expects to publish the new franchise agreements for the Northern and TransPennine Express franchise awards.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","21127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442736","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>In 2014/15, the Government provided £950 million to local highway authorities for highways maintenance, including £168 million to specifically tackle potholes across the country.</p><br /><p>In March 2014, the Government provided an additional £183.5 million to help repair local highway infrastructure damaged by the winter floods of 2013/14. This funding was spent by local highway authorities in 2014/15.</p><br /><p>Overall, between 2010 to 2015, local highways maintenance funding was 27% or £1billion higher than under the previous Labour administration.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-11T15:22:27.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442736/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442736/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 17 December 2015 to Question 20054, what funding was allocated to the Winter Weather Repair Fund in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","21128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442737","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>We are keen that operators significantly increase the uptake of smart ticketing across all franchises and we have challenged the industry to move forward with the development of new ticketing technologies. We are working with the Rail Delivery Group to work out what would need to be specified in franchises, but it is too early to say what those specifications could look like.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-11T15:12:00.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442737/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442737/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 5 January 2016 to Question 20639, whether franchise agreements for future franchises within the South East Flexible Ticketing geographical area will include an obligation for operators to subscribe to that programme.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","21126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442738","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>Pursuant to the Answer of 5 January 2016 to Question 20640, we remain committed to our modernisation programme of over 850 miles of electrification.</p><br /><p>Sir Peter Hendy’s review of the rail upgrade programme details that the vast majority of programmes and projects will go ahead for delivery by 2019 (the end of Control Period 5).</p><br /><p>However, some schemes are more immature in their development and, whilst schemes in this category will have significant delivery within Control Period 5, these schemes will span more than one control period.</p><br /><p>Electrification provides long-term efficiencies for the railways, but it is just one element of a wider set of railway upgrades to provide better journeys for passengers and freight users.</p><br />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-11T15:06:17.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442738/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442738/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 5 January 2016 to Question 20640, how many miles of track will be electrified by the end of Control Period 5 under the timetable for project delivery contained in Sir Peter Hendy's review of the rail upgrade programme.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","21125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442739","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>The new Northern Franchisee is expected to receive subsidy payments during each year of its franchise term. I note however, that under this franchise agreement the amount of annual subsidy will be reduced by £160million by the end of this 9-year contract and at the same time, unlike the last Northern franchise in 2004 which included limited plans to invest in services or meet demand, this new franchise will deliver more than 2,000 extra services each week, nearly a 40% increase in capacity and the complete removal of the outdated and unpopular Pacers by the end of 2019.</p><br /><p>The subsidy payments are set out below in both nominal terms and in real (i.e. constant) terms in 2015/16 prices. Years 1 to 9 are the payments for the core Franchise Term. Year 10 is an optional extension period of up to one year, callable at the discretion of the Secretary of State.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>£M</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><strong>Nominal</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Real – 2015/16 prices</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 1</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>281</p></td><td><p>275</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 2</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>276</p></td><td><p>262</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 3</p></td><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>282</p></td><td><p>260</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 4</p></td><td><p>2019/20</p></td><td><p>247</p></td><td><p>221</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 5</p></td><td><p>2020/21</p></td><td><p>204</p></td><td><p>177</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 6</p></td><td><p>2021/22</p></td><td><p>158</p></td><td><p>134</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 7</p></td><td><p>2022/23</p></td><td><p>136</p></td><td><p>113</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 8</p></td><td><p>2023/24</p></td><td><p>114</p></td><td><p>92</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 9</p></td><td><p>2024/25</p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year 10</p></td><td><p>2025/26</p></td><td><p>53</p></td><td><p>39</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-11T15:00:38.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442739/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442739/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what (a) premium and (b) subsidy payments the new Northern franchisee is expected to make or receive in each year of that franchise's duration.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","21124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442740","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>The Department for Transport has made no specific assessment of the economic effects of international services stopping at Stratford International station. The Department for Transport has no powers to specify that an international operator – whether current or future – must stop at Stratford International station. The Department for Transport has recently published an interim evaluation of the impact of the HS1 network setting out the current and anticipated benefits of the HS1 link<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup>.</p><br /><p><sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hs1-first-interim-evaluation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hs1-first-interim-evaluation</a></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-11T16:07:41.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442740/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442740/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Stratford Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the economic effect on (a) London and (b) the UK economy of international services stopping at Stratford International station.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","21099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442741","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<br /><p>The Department employed six individuals as contract staff at various times (sometimes covering the same role consecutively) for the Northern competition, and five for the TransPennine Competition. Costs of those staff were £1.203M and £1.275M respectively.</p><br /><p>These costs however need to be set against the context of the deals achieved, whereby for Northern the amount of annual subsidy will be reduced by £160million by the end of the 9-year contract and for TransPennine the Government will receive £400million in premiums over the life of the franchise, compared to the previous situation where the franchise was subsidised.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-11T15:58:27.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442741/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442741/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answers of 16 December 2015 to Questions 19325 and 19326, how many staff in his Department were employed on a contract basis to procure the (a) Northern and (b) TransPennine franchise agreements; and what the total cost to the public purse was of those staff.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","21114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442742","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Government has made no assessment of a Transmanche Metro. The efficacy of a route would be for the market to determine.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-12T15:41:20.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442742/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442742/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Railways: Kent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the potential efficacy of the Transmarche Metro proposal connecting Kent with the Nord-Pas-de-Calais; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","21046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442743","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>Schedule 10.2 of the TSGN Franchise Agreement (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/488198/tsgn-franchise-agreement.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/488198/tsgn-franchise-agreement.pdf</a> p.506) specifies how this franchise can be terminated by the Department.</p><br />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-11T16:18:00.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442743/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442743/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Southern","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, under which circumstances Southern Railway's franchise would be withdrawn.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","21097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442744","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>On 15<sup>th</sup> December 2015, the Office for Rail and Road published the latest in a series of Estimates of Station Usage for 2014/15, for all stations in Great Britain.</p><br /><p>They estimate that in 2014/15, 30,974,204 people travelled to or from Stratford and 3,053,317 people interchanged at Stratford.</p><br /><p>By 2026, Transport for London’s forecasts indicate that passenger movements at Stratford – including those resulting from Crossrail services stopping there - will see an increase of around 20% on the 2014 passenger numbers.</p><br />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-11T16:11:17.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442744/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442744/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Stratford Station: Passengers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many passengers use Stratford station annually; and how this number is expected to change following completion of Crossrail.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","21100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442745","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>For people living and working near airports, safety is best achieved by ensuring the safe operation of aircraft in flight.However, in areas of greater risk, we seek to control the number of people at risk through the Public Safety Zone (PSZ) system.Public Safety Zones are areas of land at the ends of the runways at the busiest airports, within which development is restricted in order to control the number of people on the ground at risk of death or injury in the event of an aircraft accident on take-off or landing. The implementation of Public Safety Zone policy at civil airports is based on modelling work carried out using appropriate aircraft accident data to determine the level of risk to people on the ground around airports.</p><br /> <br /><br /> <br /> <br /><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-11T14:31:02.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442745/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442745/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","London Airports: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what comparative assessment his Department has made of the potential damage to housing and infrastructure and loss of life that would result from an aircraft crashing on approach or arrival at Heathrow and Gatwick Airports.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","20996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442746","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-12","<br /><p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) does not record information about the sex of any complainant. Nor does it retain information about complaints made before 2011-12 about practical driving tests or cases referred to the ICA. Information it does hold is as follows:</p><p>2011-12 1,080 complaints received – 42 upheld, 938 not upheld, 100 no outcome recorded</p><p>2012-13 1,108 complaints received – 40 upheld, 1002 not upheld, 66 no outcome recorded</p><p>2013-14 1,260 complaints received – 37 upheld, 1013 not upheld, 210 no outcome recorded</p><p>2014-15 1,401 complaints received – 27 upheld, 1158 not upheld, 216 no outcome recorded</p><p>2015- 16 1,351 complaints received – 37 upheld, 1174 not upheld, 140 no outcome recorded</p><br /><p>Complaints referred to the ICA</p><p>2011-12 - 3 cases</p><p>2012-13 - 9 cases</p><p>2013-14 - 10 cases</p><p>2015-16 - 4 cases</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-12T15:29:07.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442746/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442746/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Driving Tests: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many complaints about practical driving tests heard by the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (a) were made by (i) men and (ii) women and (b) were found (i) in favour of and (ii) against the complainant; and how many such complaints were subsequently taken to the Independent Complaints Assessor in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442747","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-12","<p>This Government does not intend to amend primary legislation to allow the number of private hire vehicles licensed in London or elsewhere to be restricted.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-12T14:52:29.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442747/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442747/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Taxis: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to introduce a cap on the number of private hire vehicles operating in London.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","20981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442748","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency has a complaints procedure, which is published on GOV.UK.</p><br /><p>Current law does not allow the test result to be overturned; the examiner’s decision is final.</p><br /><p>Complainants have the right to appeal if they think the examiner did not carry out their practical test in line with regulations.</p><br /><p>If the complainant lives in England and Wales, they have six months after the test date to appeal to the Magistrates court about the way the test was conducted. The Magistrates court can look at whether the test was carried out in accordance with regulations; however, it cannot change the result of the test. Should the Magistrates court find that the test was not conducted in line with regulations, it may offer a compensation payment or free retest.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-12T15:33:49.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442748/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442748/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Driving Tests: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many appeals on practical driving tests were (a) heard by the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency and (b) found (i) in favour of and (ii) against the appellant in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442749","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Government has the most ambitious programme of rail upgrades since Victorian times. It will introduce a new fleet of Intercity Express trains, cut journey times, increase the number of seats, and provide a more reliable service for commuters and people in England and Wales. Electrifying the Great Western Main Line from London to Swansea is a UK Government commitment which we will deliver to Cardiff within Control Period 5 and to Swansea as early as possible in Control Period 6.</p><br /><p>In addition the Government is providing £10.4m, in support of the Liverpool City Region Growth Deal, to fund the reinstatement of the Halton Curve which will enable passenger services from North Wales and West Cheshire to directly access Liverpool City Centre and Liverpool John Lennon airport for the first time in decades. The Halton Curve rail link will provide large economic benefits to the Liverpool city region and surrounding areas including North Wales.</p><br /><p>We are working closely with the Welsh Government on the development of the next Rail Investment Strategy to ensure that relevant English and Welsh priorities for rail investment in Control Period 6 are reflected.</p><br /><p>On the strategic road network, Highways England’s Pinch Point Scheme at the junction of the A55 and A483 trunk roads between Chester and Wrexham was completed in June 2015.This addresses significant traffic congestion problems at this junction near the border with Wales and related road safety problems, especially during peak periods, and will help to stimulate economic growth.</p><br /><p>The Government’s first ever Road Investment Strategy has committed £15.2 billion investment for the strategic road network in England from 2015 to 2021. The next iteration of route strategies will inform investment decisions for the next Road Investment Strategy and Highways England will engage with stakeholders to identify future investment priorities.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-12T15:02:22.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442749/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442749/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Transport: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to improve major transport links between England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","20903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442750","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-12","<p>The responsibility for clearing highway litter and sweeping carriageways is governed by the Environmental Protection Act 1990. Each individual highway authority is responsible for clearing litter on the roads for which they are responsible. In the case of some all-purpose trunk roads, the responsibility for clearing litter falls to the local district councils.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-12T15:38:01.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442750/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442750/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Roads: Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the powers local councils hold to prevent littering on roads.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","20901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442751","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>The Department does not issue its own guidance. The selection of a shipping register (flag State) is a commercial decision for ship owners.</p><br /><p>However, owners can take account of the assessment of a flag State’s performance. The flag’s performance is published in the annual Paris Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) report on Port State Control. These reports can be found on the Paris MoU website at</p><p><a href="https://www.parismou.org/publications-category/annual-reports" target="_blank">https://www.parismou.org/publications-category/annual-reports</a>.</p><br /> <br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-11T15:27:05.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442751/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442751/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Shipping: Flags","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department's guidance is on shipping flags it considers unsafe or dangerous to sail under; and how often that guidance is updated.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","20917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442752","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>The South East Flexible Ticketing programme is already under way. c2c and Govia Thameslink Railway already offer annual season tickets on smartcards. Abellio Greater Anglia, South West Trains and Southeastern will launch their products this year. Together, these five train operators cover 73% of the annual season ticket market.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-11T15:48:21.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442752/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442752/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Railways: Season Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the South East flexible ticketing programme to commence.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","20918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442753","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>Network Rail does not hold this information centrally. To retrieve the information from Network Rail would involve disproportionate cost.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-11T15:53:48.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442753/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442753/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Network Rail: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Network Rail staff are seconded to which train operating companies; and what the value is of those staff contracts.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","20919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442754","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Government has regular discussions with the industry on a range of issues, and will continue to press for a fair deal for the travelling public.</p><br /><p>The airline industry is intensely competitive and there is no evidence of any market failure that would prevent cost savings being passed onto customers.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-12T15:08:58.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442754/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442754/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Aviation: Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has had with UK airlines on passing reductions in fuel costs on to passengers.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","20895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442755","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>A copy of the letter is attached. Please note that names and details of officials below the level of Senior Civil Servant, and those of non-government officials, have been redacted.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-11T15:39:47.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442755/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442755/answer","020950 - 151118 Letter to ORR - Manchester Airport (final)_Redacted.pdf","020950 - 151118 Letter to ORR - Manchester Airport (final)_Redacted.pdf","Letter from DfT to ORR","Letter from DfT to ORR","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442755/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Manchester Airport: Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 5 January 2016 to Question 20298, if he will publish the letter the Department wrote to the Office of Rail and Road in connection with the application from Arriva Trains Wales for additional train paths to and from Manchester Airport.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","20950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442756","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>The flood recovery envoy for Yorkshire, the Minister of State for Transport (Mr Goodwill), convened a meeting on January 7 2016 with North Yorkshire County Council, wider local representatives, the military and Highways England experts to finalise a plan for reconstructing Tadcaster Bridge. The Government is providing £3.3m of funding immediately to repair the bridge. It has incurred substantial damage and the current estimate is that it will take up to a year to repair.</p><br /><p>The Department for Transport is working closely with affected local highway authorities following the recent storms encountered in some areas of the country. As part of this work, local highway authorities are assessing the damage caused and likely estimated costs. It is too early to provide an estimate of the repairs or likely timescales until all waters have receded.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","21011","2016-01-11T14:08:56.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442756/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442756/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Roads: Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for (a) reconstructing Tadcaster bridge and (b) other areas of road infrastructure damaged by recent flooding identified as national priorities.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","21012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442757","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>The Electric Vehicle Homecharge Scheme was introduced in August 2014. In the period from September to December of that year there were 3,744 claims for grants. In the period January to November 2015 there were 12,435 claims for grants. The Office for Low Emission Vehicles is currently processing claims for grants made in December 2015.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-11T14:12:46.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442757/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442757/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Electric Vehicles: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many claims for grants have been made under the electric vehicle homecharge scheme in each year since its introduction.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","21010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442758","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-11","<p>The flood recovery envoy for Yorkshire, the Minister of State for Transport (Mr Goodwill), convened a meeting on January 7 2016 with North Yorkshire County Council, wider local representatives, the military and Highways England experts to finalise a plan for reconstructing Tadcaster Bridge. The Government is providing £3.3m of funding immediately to repair the bridge. It has incurred substantial damage and the current estimate is that it will take up to a year to repair.</p><br /><p>The Department for Transport is working closely with affected local highway authorities following the recent storms encountered in some areas of the country. As part of this work, local highway authorities are assessing the damage caused and likely estimated costs. It is too early to provide an estimate of the repairs or likely timescales until all waters have receded.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","21012","2016-01-11T14:08:56.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442758/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442758/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Roads: Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, where repairs to (a) the Strategic Road Network and (b) other key local roads are required in each region following recent flooding; and what estimate he has made of those repairs.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","21011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442759","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-12","<p>The railway is funded by both taxpayers and passengers. Network Rail own the infrastructure, not the train operators. The government is using the increased revenue, which is paid in franchise premiums to the Department for Transport, to help fund Network Rail’s investment programme. This will see them spend over £38 billion in the period 2014-19 on maintaining and improving rail infrastructure, in the biggest and most comprehensive programme of railway modernisation since the Victorians.</p><br /> <br />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-01-12T15:21:42.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442759/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442759/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-05","Railways: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will press rail companies to use increases in revenue to invest and upgrade rail infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","21157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442760","Wales Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Prime Minister believes Britain’s best future lies within a reformed European Union. He is focused on addressing the concerns of the British people and is confident that the right agreement can be reached.</p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2016-01-13T16:16:26.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442760/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442760/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-01-05","UK Membership of EU: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment he has made of the effect on Wales if the UK voted to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","20952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442761","Women and Equalities","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Government believes that public life is strengthened by the participation of people with different skills, backgrounds and experiences, from right across the country. As a country we cannot afford to waste the talents of half our population and that is why we must ensurewomenare better representedacross all walks of life, including those from rural areas.</p><p>The 2015 General Election was a great step forward for women’s representation. We now have the highest number of female MPs in Parliament and a third of our Cabinet is made up of women. We know women continue to be under-represented on local councils; that is why schemes such as the Be a Councillor campaign, which has been run by the Local Government Association since 2012, are so important. The Government is also committed to increasing the diversity of public appointments and has set the aspiration that 50% of new appointments should go to women.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-01-12T17:11:47.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442761/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442761/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-01-05","Females: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps she is taking to promote opportunities for women in rural areas to participate in public life.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","21030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442762","Women and Equalities","false","2016-01-11","<p>The highest salary for a woman in the Government Equalities Office (GEO) is between £90,000 and £94,999.</p><br /><p>The highest salary for a man in GEO is between £75,000 and £79,999.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-01-11T12:55:16.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442762/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442762/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-01-05","Government Equalities Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what the highest salary is of a (a) woman and (b) man in the Government Equalities Office.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","21083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442763","Women and Equalities","false","2016-01-11","<p>35 female and 20 male members of staff currently work in the Government Equalities Office.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-01-11T12:56:44.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442763/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442763/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-01-05","Government Equalities Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many people of each gender work in the Government Equalities Office.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","21084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442764","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-11","<p>The information requested is not currently available.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-11T16:39:37.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442764/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442764/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-05","Universal Credit: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applicants for Universal Credit have requested split payments on the grounds of domestic abuse since the launch of universal credit in the pilot areas; and what proportion of the total number of applicants have so claimed.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","21059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442765","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-11","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-11T16:43:04.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442765/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442765/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-05","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment the Government has made of the number of additional claimants of (a) working tax credit (WTC) and (b) the universal credit version of WTC who will have to report a change of circumstances to HM Revenue and Customs year-on-year after the in-year income rise disregard for both benefits is reduced from April 2016; and how many such claimants will see their entitlement (i) reduced and (ii) increased.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442766","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-11","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-11T16:39:26.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442766/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442766/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-05","Working Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of possible factors that would trigger a change in circumstances for a working tax credit claimant who has been transferred from universal credit (UC) which would cause their tax credit entitlement to be re-assessed based on UC thresholds.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442767","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-11","<p><strong></strong>We estimate that around 250,000 Pension Credit recipients will have their assessed income period (AIP) end early. This estimate is based on DWP administrative data and includes an assumption about the number of new AIPs that will be set between now and 5 April 2016. The end of an AIP does not necessarily change the Pension Credit award; the effect depends on whether any changes to income or capital have taken place.</p><br /> <br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-11T14:33:14.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442767/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442767/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-05","Pension Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of how many pensioners will have the assessed income periods of their pension credit end early as a result of changes to pension credit on 6 April 2016.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442768","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-11","<p>This policy is still under development and full impact and equality impact assessments will be undertaken in due course.</p><p>This measure is not being introduced until April 2018 and only then where new tenancies have been taken out or existing tenancies renewed from 1 April 2016.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-11T13:33:51.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442768/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442768/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-05","Local Housing Allowance: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what impact assessment he has made of the Government's proposal to limit housing benefit for claimants in the social housing sector to local housing allowance rates from 2018.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","21145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443524","Home Office","false","2016-01-11","<p>On 16 December the Prime Minister informed the House we had met our commitment of resettling 1,000 Syrians before Christmas. These refugees form part of the 20,000 that we will resettle during this Parliament, showing that Britain will continue to act in the finest traditions of providing shelter to the most vulnerable.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-01-11T16:27:56.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443524/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443524/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-05","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken to resettle Syrian refugees.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","902920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443525","Home Office","false","2016-01-11","<p>It is the role of Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary to assess police forces in England and Wales on their efficiency, including how they are managing demand for services and whether they have appropriate systems in place to assess trends. Their most recent assessment (report published October 2015) found that forces have a good understanding of current demand but need to improve their understanding of future demand. Forces are working with the College of Policing to progress this work.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-01-11T16:50:17.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443525/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443525/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-05","Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of trends in the level of demand for police services.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","902906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443526","Home Office","false","2016-01-11","<p>We have established an Organised Immigration Crime Taskforce of 100 officers from the NCA, Crown Prosecution Service, and the Home Office to disrupt organised immigration crime groups upstream, including through the Mediterranean routes, and in the UK. The UK is also supporting the EU Naval Forces Operation in the Mediterranean. We are determined to disrupt organised immigration criminal activities which impact adversely on our security and have such a wanton disregard for human life.</p><br /><br />","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-01-11T16:35:46.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443526/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443526/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-05","Human Trafficking: Mediterranean Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what support the Government is providing to tackle people-smuggling in the Mediterranean.","false","Biography information for Lord Davies of Gower","Gower","Byron Davies","902925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443527","Home Office","false","2016-01-11","<p>The Immigration Act 2014 and related changes have expedited the removal of over 2,000 foreign national offenders from this country and stopped illegal migrants having access to services such as bank accounts, driving licences and rented accommodation.</p><p>The Immigration Bill will go further, enabling the seizure of earnings from illegal workers, further penalising rogue employers, and extending the deport first, appeal later principle to more cases.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-01-11T16:33:52.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443527/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443527/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-05","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to prevent abuse of the immigration system.","false","Biography information for David Rutley","Macclesfield","David Rutley","902922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444400","Wales Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>I fully support the campaign to return His Royal Highness the Prince of Wales' regalia to Wales, in this the 40<sup>th</sup> Anniversary Year of the Prince’s Trust. There has been a lot of interest in this for a number of years and I welcome the agreement of HM the Queen for the symbolic regalia to be displayed in Llandovery.</p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2016-01-13T15:50:18.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444400/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444400/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-01-05","Cultural Heritage: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what progress the Government has made on the return of the Prince of Wales' regalia to Wales.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","902952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444401","Wales Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Welsh Government is responsible for the NHS in Wales. It is up to the Welsh Government to decide how best to use their funding and deliver health services in Wales.</p><p>The UK Government is happy to share good practice with the Welsh Government to help ensure people living in Wales receive high quality healthcare.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-01-13T15:49:04.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444401/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/444401/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-01-05","NHS: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent discussions he has had with the Welsh Government on the cost efficiency of the NHS in Wales compared with England.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Turner","Isle of Wight","Mr Andrew Turner","902949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442228","Attorney General","false","2016-01-07","<p>During 2014-2015 the CPS prosecuted 187 defendants for offences connected with human trafficking. 130 of these defendants were convicted at a conviction rate of 69.5%.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-01-07T11:34:06.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442228/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442228/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-01-04","Human Trafficking: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, pursuant to the Answer of 15 December 2015 to Question 19543, how many of those prosecutions for human trafficking resulted in a conviction.","false","Biography information for Mark Field","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","20819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442229","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Department published a detailed progress report on the implementation of the Kay Review in October 2014.</p><br /><p>The Government’s Productivity Plan, “Fixing the Foundations”, published in July 2015, emphasised the central importance of encouraging long-term business investment as part of an ambitious vision to boost productivity in the UK economy. In particular, the Plan welcomed an initiative by several of the largest institutional investors to develop an Action Plan to support and challenge companies to invest for long-term productivity and growth. The Government is engaging with the Investment Association as it takes forward this work, and is also considering what further steps may be appropriate to encourage a culture of long-term investment on the part of UK companies and their shareholders.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-12T16:02:36.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442229/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442229/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-04","Effect of UK Equity Markets on the Competitiveness of UK Business Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps the Government has taken to follow up the recommendations in the Kay Review of UK equity markets and long-term decision making, published in July 2012.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","20814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442230","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-12","<p><strong></strong></p><br /><p>My Department has had discussions with the London Legacy Development Corporation (LLDC) about papers, prepared by the LLDC, for the Competition Directorate General of the European Commission. These papers explained the contractual arrangements relating to West Ham United Football Club's use of the Olympic Stadium.</p><br /><p>I can confirm that the Commission considered these papers and reached a preliminary assessment that the contractual arrangements did not involve state aid and decided not to pursue their investigation any further.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-12T15:59:42.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442230/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442230/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-04","West Ham United Football Club: Sportsgrounds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department has had discussions with the London Legacy Development Corporation about EU state aid rules and West Ham United Football Club's occupancy of the Olympic Stadium.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","20797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442231","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-11","<br /><p>The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost. However details of Ministers’ overseas travel are published quarterly on the Gov.uk website:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-business-innovation-skills&amp;publication_type=transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-business-innovation-skills&amp;publication_type=transparency-data</a></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-01-11T17:24:26.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442231/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442231/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-04","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which countries have not had an official visit by a Minister in his Department since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","20745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442232","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Post Office is the largest provider of counter-based Government services in the UK. In 2013 it won a cross-Government framework contract which allows all Government Departments and their Executive Agencies to contract with the Post Office easily and cheaply. Key contracts with the DVLA and the Passport Office have been moved onto this new framework, as has the Post Office Card Account contract which has been extended to at least 2021.</p><br /><p>The Post Office is well-placed to bid for and win important contracts, with its extensive geographic reach and key role in the heart of communities. Government cannot simply award contracts to the Post Office; services must be procured competitively to ensure value for taxpayers’ money.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-01-12T15:49:14.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442232/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442232/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-04","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what progress he has made on making the Post Office a front office for Government; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","20767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442233","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-11","<br /><p>The business case for the Inspiring Science Capital Fund is currently being developed with science stakeholders, and is expected to go through the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills Investment Gateway process within the next two months. No funding can be confirmed until the business case is agreed.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-01-11T17:00:03.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442233/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442233/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-04","Inspiring Science Capital Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the timetable is for developing the business case for the Inspiring Science Capital Fund.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","20757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442234","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-12","<br /><p>The prior qualification survey is the current method for collecting robust information on the prior qualification levels of apprentices. The most recent publication is based on the 2012/13 survey data. We plan to publish a similar report based on the 2013/14 prior qualifications survey data in 2016.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-12T17:51:12.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442234/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442234/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-04","Apprentices: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if his Department will collect data on the prior qualification level of new apprentices.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","20728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442235","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-15","<p><strong></strong></p><br /><p>A consultation was held during summer 2015 on proposals to increase the maximum custodial sentence for online copyright infringement from two to ten years, to harmonise it with the penalty available for physical infringement. The responses to that consultation have been analysed and officials at the IPO are now giving consideration to future direction and timing and will advise Ministers accordingly.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-15T14:50:04.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442235/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442235/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-04","Copyright: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what plans he has to bring forward legislative proposals on increasing penalties for online copyright infringement.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","20753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442236","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-13","<p>UK Trade and Investment (UKTI) supports UK companies who want to grow their business overseas. We provide tailored support packages for companies from first time exporters to medium sized businesses, whilst also providing digital and online support to all businesses. We continue to proactively support UK renewable companies and recognise the huge potential in developing country markets. Support from UK Export Finance (principally in the form of insurance to exporters, guarantees to banks and loans to overseas buyers) is also available for UK exporters in all sectors including the renewable energy sector.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-13T17:03:57.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442236/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442236/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-04","Renewable Energy: Overseas Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what support his Department provides to UK-based renewable energy companies seeking to invest in developing country markets; how many companies in that sector have received such support; and what steps he is taking to increase such support (a) in general and (b) through export guarantees.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","20744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442237","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-13","<br /><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has no current plans to introduce legislation to prohibit the use of expiry dates on gift cards.</p><br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-13T17:43:02.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442237/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442237/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-04","Gift Cards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether he plans to bring forward legislative proposals to prohibit expiry dates on gift cards.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","20830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442238","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-12","<p>Since 2008 six licences have been granted that relate to the sale of complete Eurofighter Typhoon aircraft to Saudi Arabia. Four of these licences are linked. Where licences expired before they were fully exhausted the exporter submitted a new application to cover those aircraft not exported under previous licences. The values therefore relate to exports licensed rather than actual exports.</p><br /><p>Typhoon transfers per year are declared in the UK Strategic Export Controls Annual Reports and can be found on GOV.UK</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Value of Licence(s)</p></td><td><p>Licence Extant or Expired?</p></td><td><p>Licence used in full or in part</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br> 2009</p></td><td><p><br> £1,476,666,648</p></td><td><p><br> Expired</p></td><td><p><br> Used in part</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£1,555,833,315</p></td><td><p>Expired</p></td><td><p>Used in part</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£129,652,776</p></td><td><p>Expired</p></td><td><p>Used in full</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£1,564,666,650</p></td><td><p>Expired</p></td><td><p>Used in part</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 2015</p></td><td><p>£1,564,666,650 £129,652,776</p></td><td><p>Extant Extant</p></td><td><p>Used in part Used in part</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-12T16:48:54.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442238/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442238/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-04","European Fighter Aircraft: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and S