ne","Angela Rayner","20888"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442353","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-01-12T12:18:00.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442353/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442353/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-04","Physiotherapy: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many NHS respiratory physiotherapists work with people with muscle wasting conditions in (a) Nottingham, (b) Nottinghamshire and (c) the East Midlands.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","20862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442354","Department of Health","false","2016-01-07","<p>This information is not available in the format requested.</p><br /><p>Official statistics for NHS trusts in England are published by NHS England on the number of patients delayed on the last Thursday of each month and the total delayed days during the month for all patients delayed throughout the month. The latest publication of this data was for delays occurring in October 2015 and was published on 10 December 2015.</p><br /><p>It is not possible to calculate a montly average or the longest waits from these data. Health is a devolved matter in Wales.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","20855 ; 20856 ; 20857 ; 20858","2016-01-07T11:43:47.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442354/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442354/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-04","Hospital Beds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the longest a patient waited for discharge from hospital after being declared fit to leave was in (a) England and Wales, (b) London and (c) each health trust in London in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","20854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442355","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Department is currently preparing to go out to public consultation on the introduction of fixed recoverable costs (FRC) for clinical negligence claims as originally proposed by Lord Woolf and Lord Justice Jackson in 1996 and 2009 respectively. The consultation will include consideration on the maximum value of claims that will be covered by the FRC regime and whether there should be any exemptions. We will review all responses before making a final decision on these issues.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-01-12T14:53:06.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442355/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442355/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-04","NHS: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether it is his policy that costs in fatal cases involving a claim for less than £25,000, including the costs of representation at inquest, will fall outside of the proposed fixed recoverable costs in clinical negligence schemes.","false","Biography information for Lord Garnier","Harborough","Sir Edward Garnier","20803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442356","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>NHS England offers BRCA testing to individuals with a greater than 10% chance of carrying the mutation, using a model based on the individual’s personal and family history of cancers. Data is not collected centrally on reasons for women choosing to take a test for the BRCA1/2 gene mutation.</p><br /><p>The UK Genetic Testing Network is working with NHS England, the devolved administrations and the Health and Social Care Information Centre to collect and publish United Kingdom-wide data on molecular genetic testing activity. Data collection is expected to have been completed by the summer of 2016 with a full update prepared for publication by the end of the year. However, it is not intended that this will include specific data for BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutation testing activity.</p><br />","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","20802 ; 20877","2016-01-12T15:11:31.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442356/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442356/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-04","Genetics: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the reasons for women choosing to take a test for the BRCA1/2 gene mutation.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","20801"
